•	Performance and Capacity Assessment
Evaluate capacity utilization trends and forecast future storage needs based on growth rates.
Measure performance metrics (throughput, IOPS, latency) of the existing storage systems under typical workloads.
I/O Performance Metrics: Measure Input/output Operations per Second (IOPS), throughput, and latency benchmarks to understand the storage system's performance capabilities. This evaluation provides insights into how quickly data can be read from or written to the storage.
Workload Analysis: Analyze the specific workloads and applications that will utilize the storage system. Different workloads (such as transactional databases, analytics, virtualization, or content delivery) have unique I/O patterns, influencing the choice of storage solution.
Storage Architecture: Evaluate the storage architecture.
Storage Tiering and Caching: Assess if the storage solution supports tiering and caching mechanisms. These features optimize performance by automatically moving frequently accessed data to faster storage tiers or utilizing caching for quicker access.
RAID Configurations: Evaluate the RAID (Redundant Array of Independent Disks) configurations supported by the storage solution. Different RAID levels offer varying levels of performance, capacity, and fault tolerance. Choose a configuration that aligns with your performance needs.
Data Reduction and Compression: Check if the storage solution offers data reduction techniques like deduplication and compression. These features can optimize storage capacity utilization and indirectly improve performance by reducing data transfer requirements.
Proof of Concept (PoC): Conduct real-world performance tests or PoCs with sample workloads to validate the claimed performance metrics and understand how the storage solution performs in your specific environment.
Vendor Support: Evaluate the vendor's commitment ongoing support.

